ation whose ingenuity encouraged the development of this new form of devotional technology. It is the first full-length study to focus in depth on the materiality of these tabernacles, investigating the connotations and effects of the materials from which they were made. It examines especially the effect of bringing relics and images together, and considers how the impressions of variety and abundance created by the multiplication of materials give birth to meaning and encourage certain kinds of action or thought.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aArt & Architecture. 4aMedieval History. 7aART / Subjects & Themes / Religious.2bisacsh  aItaly.  aimage.  amaterial culture.  amedieval art.  arelic.  areliquary tabernacles.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805433453?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805433453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805433453/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles